{"/service/ndnp/mdu/batch_mdu_frederick_ver03/data/sn89060127/00279522035/1938012801/0062.xml":{"full_text":"Page 6\nWORCESTER DEMOCRAT\nAND\nTHE LEDGER-ENTERPRISE\nPublished Every Friday at Pocomoke City, Maryland.\nEDWARD J. CLARKE, Editor and Owner\n$1.60 The Year In Advance.\nEntered at the Postoffice at Pocomoke City, Maryland, as Second Class Matter\nra \\i t, NATIONAL EDITORIAL\nBe^ soc,atw\nFRIDAY, JANUARY 28, 1938\nPOLITICS DOMINATING BUSINESS\nAs a business magazine recently said, \u201cIt was to Washington\nthat business looked this week for clues to what\u2019s ahead. That\nhas been largely true ever since 1929. It is prabobly more tine\ntoday than it ever was before. Politics has become the dominating\nfactor in the business situation and the business outlook.\nNumber one late Washington occurrence was the President\u2019s\nstatement, made at a press conference, to the effect that he wish\nes the ultimate destruction of all holding companies. He specifi\ncally mentioned ,banking holding companies, but did not further\nelaborate his views. The Public Utility Act of 1935\u2014whose con\nstitutionality will be finally decided by the Supreme Court this\nterm\u2014demonstrated the Administration\u2019s policy of eliminating\nholding companies in the public utility field, but up to now no one\nbelieved the President was looking into other fields. His state\nment was greeted with both wonder and amazement in financial\ncircles, which pointed out that about half of all the widely-held\nlisted securities represent concerns which are wholly or partly\nholding companies by nature, and said that it would be impossible\nto accurately gauge the effect of a wholesale anti-holding company\npolicy until Mr. Roosevelt clarifies and explains his views and pur\nposes.\nThe holding company declaration, coming on top of the recently\ninaugurated anti-monopoly movement, further illustrates the wid\nening breech between an Administration which is still clinging to\nits original more or less revolutionary objectives, and a Congress\nwhich seems to be daily turning more conservative and dubious of\nWhite House policies. It likewise further emphasizes the tre\nmendous cleavage of opinion that exists between the Administra\ntion and American business-at-large.\nLess-headlined, but of unusual interest, was an \u201cinvestiga\ntion\u201d on the subject of employment which a Senate committee re\ncently held. As Time says, \u201cTo the public generally, a Senate in\nvestigation means a scandal hunt.\u201d This one was very different\n\u2014the committee honestly wanted information, and the questions\nasked were generally designed to achieve just that, not to smear\nthe questionee.\nOne witness was Federal Reserve Chairman Eccles, represen\ntative of right-wing Administration opinion. Mr. Eccles, who\nhas long advocated immediate budget-balancing, attributed the\nbusiness slump to the soldiers\u2019 bonus payment, which accentuat\ned inflationary sentiment, and to strikes, increased operating\ncosts for the railroads, lack of expansion by utilities and the gov\nernment\u2019s effort to reduce its contribution to consumer spending\npower. He said it was necessary to reduce \u201cmonopolistically con\ntrolled prices and wages which are now too high.\u201d\nAnother witness was General Motors\u2019 William Knudsen, who\ndescribed the dilemma in the automotive industry, the amazingly\nfast drop in new and used car buying, spoke of \u201cfear psychology\u201d\nas a factor in producing bad times, and attributed this in part to\ngovernment\u2019s attitude toward business. A similar opinion was\nexpressed by Robert Wood, Sears Roebuck President, who said\nthat \u201cbusiness lacks confidence and is scared,\u201d and observed that\nthe businessman \u201chas ben clubbed over the head many times.\u201d Mr.\nWood also said that a number of specific factors led to the current\nslump, including: Overproduction in the spring of 1936; steriliza\ntion of gold; increased Federal Reserve requirements, and the fact\nthat private spending did not take up the slack when the govern\nment began slowing down some of its emergency activities.\nAll ol these witnesses likewise agreed that abnormally large\ninventories had contributed to the unprecedented sharpness of the\ndecline last fall and early winter. The inventory situation is grad\nually being corrected now, and in some industries recent figures\nindicate that inventories are excessively low\u2014one of the main\nfacts on which the many economists who look for an upturn this\nspring or summer put their hopes.\nSo the debate goes on. In the meantime, the actual business\nindices have not changed much lately, with improvement in some\nlines offset by further declines in others.\nFIFTY YEARS FROM NOW\nThose of us who are unduly depressed as we view the political\nstate of the world today may merely have lost our perspective. It\nis, at any rate, both consoling and stimulating to read the latest\nprophecy of that prince of prophets, 11. G. Wells. Like the rest\nof us, he has no crystal into which he gazes, but few men can com\npare with him in his amazing combination of perspective, imagina\ntion and range of awareness.\n\u201cThe common man of today,\u201d he declares, \u201cis healthier, better\ninformed, better fed, lit, clothed, housed, with greater power of\nmovement and leading a fuller and more interesting life than the\ncommon man of 1888.\u201d Life in 1988, he infers, judging from ten\ndencies in the last half century, will be less \u201ccellular\u201d than ours\u2014\nmore open, with the school-centered community replacing the\nhousehold as the social unit. Our descendants will be more free,\ncandid, agreeable and healthy than we are; their streets, roads,\ngardns, architecture and clothing will reflect this openness and\nfreedom; and their houses and clothes, particularly, will be revo\nlutionized by the new materials which science is just now begin\nning to develop.\nThis outlook, of course, is based on Mr. Wells\u2019 assumption, un\nfortunately not beyond question, that political dictatorship\u2014with\nits accompanying suppression of freedom of thought and inquiry\n\u2014is not likely to reach the point where it will prevent scientific\nprogress.\nCAUSE AND CURE\nB. C. Forbes, noted writer on subjects of economics and fi\nnance, hits the nail pretty squarely on the head, we believe, in his\nrecent article on the \u201cCauses and Cure of the Depression.\u201d\nWe possess practically every ingredient essential to prosperity\nexcept one, r. Forbes, says, and that one is confidence, lie adds:\n\u201cThis ingredient can be supplied only by Washington.\n\u201cOut of all these conferences now being held by President\nRoose. elt with men who hare played a constructive part in making\nAmerica great, it is profoundly to be hoped that good w ill come,\nthat political backbiting will subside, that cooperation will develop,\nthat re-employment will take the place of expanding uni nploy-1\nment, that good times will very shortly supplant the who\\\\ unnec\nessary bad times now causing so much suffering to our people and\nimperiling our national future.\u201d\nREAL ESTATE TRANSFERS\nElizabeth I). Sanford, frojn Aynie;\ni McGregor Purnell, the \u201cLynch Farm,\u201d\ncontaining GO acres, more or less, in\nthe 10th Elec. Dist. Consideration\n$lO &c.\nAnnie McGregor Purnell, Howard\nW. Purnell, Roland J. Purnell, Mary\nAndasia Purnell and Nellie McGreg\nor Purnell Boston from Elizabth D.\nSanford and husband, the \u201cLynch\nFarm,\u201d containing 60 acres, more or\nless, in the 10th Elec. Dist. Consid\neration $lO &c.\nNellie Pearl Warrington from Geo.\nW. Warrington and wife and others,\n50 3-4 acres, more or less, lying a\n\u201cWoodcraft\u2019s Purchase\u201d containing\nbout 1-2 mile South of Dixon\u2019s Branch\non the road from Williamsville, Del.,\nto St. Martin\u2019s Neck in the 6th Elec.\nDist. Consideration $lO &c.\nHallie P. Costopoulos from Michael\nShalas, real estate on the mainland,\nnear Ocean City and on the North;\nside of the State Stone Road leading\nfrom Berlin to Ocean City in the 10th\nElec. Dist. Consideration $lO &c.\nZelo V. Fulmer from Jas. F. Mur\nray and wife, part of the \u201cOld Latch- j\num Land,\u201d containing 30 acres, morei\nor less, in the sth Elec. Dist. Con- j\nsideration $lO &c.\nWilliam G. Kerbin, Jr., from Rodney\nC. Bounds and wife, 2 tracts of land\ncontaining 137 acres and 14 acres,\nmore or less, in Newark Elec. Dist..\nConsideration $lO &c.\nRodney C. Bounds and Bessie J.\nBounds, his wife, from Wm. G. Ker\nbin, Jr., and wife, 2 tracts of land\ncontaining 137 acres and 14 acres,\nmore or less, in Newark Elec. Dist.\nConsideration $lO &c.\nRalph S. Brown and Pauline W.\nBrown, his wife, from Safe Deposit\nand Trust Co., of Baltimore, Trustee\nand others, real estate on the South\nwest of Strawberry Alley, in Snow\nHill. Consideration $5,000.\nMaurice William Wilkins and Bet\nty Gordon Wilkins, his' wife, from\nDaniel H. Gordon and wife, real es\ntate on the mainland opposite Ocean\nCity and on the North side of the\nState Stone Road leading from Ber\nlin to Ocean City, in the 10th Elec.\nDist. Consideration $1 &c.\nOscar B. Catlin from L. Atwood\nBennett and Thos. F. Johnson, Trus\ntees, 52 acres of land, more or less,\non the West side of and binding upon\nthe County Road leading from Salis\nbury to Bounds\u2019 Election House, in the\n7th Elec. Dist. Consideration $430.\nLandy S. Riggin and Maggie V.\nRiggin, his wife, from Oscar B. Cat\nlin, real estate containing 52 acres,\nmore or less on the West side of and\nbinding upon the County Road lead\ning from Salisbury to Bounds Elec\ntion House, in the 7th Elec. Dist.\nConsideration $lO &c.\nW. Bryan Groton, James H. Vin\ncent and Leonard D. Barnes, Sr., Trus\ntees of Glad Tidings Tabernacle, from\nAlonza G. Payne, real estate at the\nNortheast Corner of Walnut and Sev\nenth Streets, in Pocomoke City. Con\nsideration $lO &c.\nw\nMiona, Va. News\nMr. and Mrs. Edwin Turlington of\nMelfa, spent the week-end with Mr.\nand Mrs. B. P. Paradee.\nMr. and Mrs. William Bunting spent\nthe week-end with Mr. and Mrs. D.\nF. Miles.\nMrs. L. L. Colona spent Monday\nwith her parents, Mr. and Mrs. B. P.\nParadee.\nMrs. Fred Tull and children, Myr\ntle Louise and Edward, spent Friday\nevening with Mrs. D. P. Miles.\nMrs. H. C. Nottingham and grand\nson, Linwood Willis, Jr., spent the\nweek-end with Mrs. F. A. Miles.\nMr. and Mrs. B. P. Paradee spent\nSunday afternoon with Mr. and Mrs.\nGeorge Chapman of Greenbackville.\nMr. F. A. Miles is in the Marine\nHospital in Baltimore, Md., for ob\nservation and treatment. We hope\nhe will be helped and soon be home\ni\nnuKCESTEK DEMOCRAT, POCOMOKE CITY, MARYLAJNiJ\ni again.\nMiss Vivian Farlow is in Salisbury i\nHospital for treatment. We wish her\nI a speedy recovery.\nWe are glad to report Miss Beulah\nParks after being critically ill is bet\nter and will soon be able to resume\nher studies at school soon.\nMr. and Mrs. A. J. Taylor were call\ners on Mrs. Taylor\u2019s mother, Sunday\nafternoon, Mrs. D. P. Miles.\nMr. and Mrs. B. P. Paradee, Mr.\nand Mrs. Clifton Trader and Mrs. Os\ncar Barnes were dinner guests of Mr.\nand Mrs. L. L. Colona, Sunday.\nMr. and Mrs. Oscar Barnes spent\nTuesday with Mr. and Mrs. B. P.\nParadee.\nMr. and Mrs. I). F. Miles and\ndaughter, Virginia, Mrs. F. A. Miles\nand sons, Richard Byrd and Prentis\nMiles and Mr. and Mrs. B. P. Paradee\nwere supper guests of Mr. and Mrs.\nHall Parks, Wednesday evening.\nMr. and Mrs. Elic Kelley, Mrs. W.\nJ. Parks, Mr. Edward Parks were\ncallers in the home of Mr. and Mrs.\nW. H. Parks, Monday evening.\nMr. and Mrs. Harvey Mason, Mr.\nand Mrs. Herbert Paradee, Mr. and\nMrs. Woodrow Wilkerson and Mr. and\nMrs. Edgar Wilkerson, were callers\non Mr. and Mrs. Elic Kelley Friday\nevening.\nURUORTAX EVADER\nTAKEN INTO CUSTODY\nCharles W. Brown, of Berlin, is be\ning held under $5,000 bond pending\naction of the United States District\nCourt following a hearing before U.\nS. Commissioner Lewis C. Merryman.\nBrown entered a plea of guilty to\na charge of possessing non-tax paid\nliquor with intent to sell.\nPublic Auction\nOF CARLOAD OF\nHorses and Mules\nAnother carload of Horses and\nMules will arrive Monday, January\n31, and will be sold at public auction\nat my stables at\nNassawadox, Va.\nSATURDAY, FEBRUARY 5, 1938\nat 2 p. m.\nThis load will be of the usual good\nquality. Their ages will be from 4\nto 6 years and they will weigh from\n900 to 1300 pounds. Better buy them\nnow, so they will be ready to go to\nwork when Spring opens up. Be\nsides prices of team are advancing\nevery day. Cattle and hogs taken\nin trade, but you can buy them cheap\ner for cash. All team must be as\nrepresented.\nWe are agents for the Hartford\nLive Stock Insurance Company and\ncan give you a policy against death\nfor $7.00 per SIOO.OO.\nFrank Bowler\nNOTICE TO CREDITORS\nNotice is hereby given that the sub\nscriber has obtained from the Or\nphans\u2019 Court for Worcester County,\nMaryland, letters of Administration\non the personal estate of Weltha\nMason, late of Worcester County, de\nceased.\nAll persons having claims against\nthe deceased, are hereby warned to ex\nhibit the same, with the vouchers\nthereof, to the subscriber on or before\nthe 18th day of July, 1938. They may\notherwise by law be excluded from all\nbenefits of the said estate. All per\nsons indebted to said estate are re\nquested to make immediate payment.\nGiven under my hand this 6th day of\nJanuary, 1938.\nJENNIE V. LAMBF.RTSON\nAdministratrix\nTest: Paul Jones, Register of Wills.\nJan 7-3 t.\nPublic Sale\nThe Cokesbury Rural Telephone\nCompany, will sell at public auc\ntion, at Wallace V. Taylor\u2019s\nStore, on January 29th, 1938, at\n10 A. M., around 300 heart ced\nar cypress telephone poles, about\n70 bundles of No. 14 wire and\na lot of insulators, the poles\neach will make from 2 to 3\nfence post, the post, wire and in\nsulators are quite suitable for\nfencing, especially electric fenc\nes.\nS. A. Evans\nSec\u2019y Treas.\nWhen you have something to sell,\nrent, or trade or have lost something,\nrun a classified in our paper. It gets\ni results when others fail.\nIN MEMORIAM\nIn memory of my dear daughter,\nBertie A. Ford, who passed away Jan\nuary 20th, 10.'57.\nPast her suffering, past her pain,\nShe who suffered is at rest,\nGone to Heaven with the blest.\nHer loving face I hope to see.\nAfter the years have passed,\nSleep on dear Bertie, take your rest;\nThey who miss you love you best.\nMother\nJan. 28-lt. i\nIN MEMORIAM\nIn loving memory of my dear father\nGordon H. Redden, who passed away\none year ago, January 27, 1937.\nMore and more each day we miss him;\nFriends may think the wound is heal\ned\nBut they little know the sorrow\nLies within our heart\u2019s concealed.\nLoving daughter,\nClara Mason\nJan. 28-ltp.\nIN MEMORIAM\nurn\nHURT\nTo and from\nthe Heart of BALTIMORE\nSchedule in effect September 12,1937\nj Eastern Standard Time)\nLEAVE LOVE POINT\n(B. E. R. R. PIER)\nDAILY ex. Son. DAILY DAILY\n1:00 a.m. MS o. m. 6:00 p.m.\nLEAVE BALTIMORE\n(PIER 5, LIGHT STREET)\nDAILY DAILY DAILY ex. Sat.\n7:00 a. m. 3:00 p. m. 9:00 p. m.\nPatiengeri, Automobile* and\nTrucks Handled on All Trip*\nPASSENGERS:\nSOr ONE 7 Kr UNI> TRIP\nWAY (4-day Hmir\nC 0 ONE DAY\nEXCURSION\nAUTOS \u20192\nTRUCKS ,N K?\u00b0 *3 to *6\nSHORTENS THE WAY BETWEEN\nBALTIMORE A THE EASTERN SHORE\nBALTIMORE EASTERN R.R.\n\nPUBLIC SALE\nOF VALUABLE\nReal Estate\nHaving decided to remove to an\nother farm, I will sell at public auc\ntion where I now reside, about 2 miles\nwest of Davis\u2019 store, and 2 miles north\nof Rehoboth school house; on\nWed., February 2,1938\nAt 10 O\u2019clock A. M.\nThe following to wit:\n1 horse, 12 years old.\n1 mule, 12 years old\n2 heifers, 1 year old\n1 farm wagon and rack\n1 John Deere riding cultivator with\nfertilizer attachment.\n1 John Deere riding plow.\n1 John Deere disc harrow\n1 Oliver No. 3 plow\n1 Oliver No. 6 plow\n1 driving mower\n1 McCormick hay rake\n3 walking cultivators\n1 spike-tooth harrow\n1 spring-tooth harrow\nHarness and other small articles,\ntoo numerous to mention.\nH. S. OVERHOLT.\nTerms: CASH.\nAuctioneer: W. D. Lankford.\nonnnppnHgpgngra^\nI Tombstones And\nMonuments\nIf we of today leave no jj\nrecord to show that those\nwe loved have lived, what *j\nis to be expected of tomor- t\nrow\u2019s generations who will\nnot know\u2014nor care.\nPocomoke Marble\nWorks\nC. K. HOWARD* Prop, jj\nPocomoke, City, Md.\nniMtHaiMPnooiaotmooaaaogacHJC\nCLAIBORNE ANNAPOLIS\nMATAPEAKE FERRIES\nSave 100 Miles\nFALL SCHEDULE\nEffective September 28th, 1937\nDAILY SUNDAY (E. S. T.)\nBetween Annapolis and Matapeake\nLEAVE LEAVE\nANNAPOLIS MATAPEAKE\n8:00 a. m. 7:25 a. m\n10:00 a. m. 9:00 a. m\n11:00 a. m. 11:00 a. m\n12:00 noon 12:00 noon\n1:00 p. m. 1:00 p. m.\n2:00 p. m. 2:00 p. m\n3:00 p. m. 3:00 p. m,\n4:00 p. m. 4:00 p. ra.\n6:00 p. m. 5:00 p. m\n8:00 p. m. 7:00 p. m\nBetween Annapolis and Claiborne\nLEAVE LEAVE\nVNNAI\u2019IMS CLAIBORNF\n\":30 a. m. 9:30 a. m\n5:00 p. m. 7:00 p. nt\nThe Claiborne-Annapolis Ferry Co.\nANNAPOLIS. MD.\nSolicitor\nMoi\nl\nRest and\nHote. .operty\non Willow Street,\nPocomoke City, Md.\nUnder and by virtue of the power of,\nsale contained in a mortgage from\nJohn W. Reid and Katherine I). Reid,\nhis wife, to John Edwin Powell, same\nbearing date August 31, 1929, and re\ncorded among the land records of\ni Worcester County, Maryland, in Liber\nB. B. No. 8, folios 133, etc., the under\nsigned trustee named therein for fore\nclosure, will offer for sale at public\nauction on\nSat., January 29, 1938\nAt the hour of Three o\u2019clock in the\nafternoon\nIn front of the Parker House,\nPocomoke City, Md.\nAll that lot or parcel of ground sit\nuate, lying and being in Pocomoke\nCity, Worcester County, Maryland, on\nthe southwest side of Willow Street,\nhaving a width on said Willow Street\nof 47 feet and a depth of 80 feet\nadjoining the property of L. Paul\nEwell on the northwest, the Armory\nof the Maryland National Guard on\nthe southwest and the property for\nmerly owned by Cornelia Davis and an\nalley on the southeast, being all and\nthe same property conveyed by the\nmortgage aforesaid, and also all and\nthe same property conveyed to the\nsaid John W. Reid and Katherine D.\nReid, as tenants by the entireties,\nfrom the said John Edwin Powell and\nwife by deed dated August 29, 1929,\nand recorded among the land records\nof Worcester County, Maryland, in\nLiber B. B. No. 7, folios 401, etc.,\ntogether with the buildings and im\nprovements thereon and all the alleys\nand ways thereto belonging or in\nanywise appertaining.\nThis property has the use in com\nmon with other owners and occupiers\nof an alley fourteen feet in width\nrunning northwesterly from Second\nStreet along the Davis property and\nalso a strip fourteen feet in width ex\ntending from the Armory property to\nthe Davis property, this strip being\nabout twenty-eight feet from said Ar\nmory property to said Davis proper\nty. This property is improved by a\nbrick and concrete restaurant and\nhotel building and is commonly called\n\u201cReid\u2019s Hotel and Restaurant.\u201d It is\nwell located and should be of interest\nto anyone desiring a good business\nproperty. There are twelve bed\nrooms.\nTerms of sale CASH.\nTitle papers and revenue tax at the\nexpense of the purchaser. Taxes paid\nto January 1, 1938. Possession on\nratification of sale.\nL. PAUL EWELL, Trustee\nJan. 7-4 t.\nThomas M. Harrington\nand\nJohn S. Whaley\nSolicitors\nAssignee\u2019s Sale\nOF VALUABLE\nFARM PROPERTY\nUnder and by virtue of the Power\nof Sale contained in a mortgage from\nSidney C. Townsend and Susie B.\nTownsend, his wife, dated January 30,\n1934, and recorded among the Land\nRecords of Worcester County, Mary\nland, in Liber B. B. No. 20, folios 524,\n525, 526,527 and 528, which said mort\ngage was duly assigned to the under\nsigned Assignee for the purpose of\nforeclosure and collection, default hav\ning occurred therein, the said under\nsigned Assignee will offer for sale at\npublic auction to the highest bidder in\nfront of the Parker House in Poco\nmoke City, Worcester County, Mary\nland, on\nSATURDAY FEB., 5,1938\nAt 2:00 O\u2019clock P. M.\nAll that tract of land containing\n85% acres, more or less, situate in the\nFirst Election District, Worcester\nCounty, Maryland, on both sides of a\ncounty road leading from McMaster\nSchool House to Tull\u2019s Mill, about five\nmiles south from Pocomoke. BEING\nall and the same land which was con\nveyed to the said Sidney C. Townsend\nfrom William S. Townsend, Executor\nof the last Will and Testament of\nSidney F. Townsend, deceased, by\ndeed dated January 31, 1918, record\ned among the aforesaid Land Records\nin Liber O. D. C. No. 30, folio 186.\nBEING ALSO all and the same prop\nerty covered by the mortgage first\nherein mentioned, to which deed and\nmortgage reference is hereby made\nfor a more particular description of\nthis land.\nThis farm is suitable for cultivation\nwith crops raised in this County and\nlocality. There are 35 acres suitable\nfor cultivation and the balance pas\nture and wood land. The property is\nimproved by a two-story frame and\nbrick dwelling with one and one-half\nstory annex, tenant house, bam and\nother outbuildings.\nTERMS OF SALE\n$500.00 cash at time and place of J\nsale, balance upon final ratification\nof said sale by the Circuit Court of\nsaid County. Taxes and other\ncharges adjusted to day .of sale. Deed\nand title papers at cost of purchaser.\nJOHN S. WHALEY, Assignee\nJan. 14-4 t.\nWhen you have something io ael.\nrent or trade run an ad in our Class\nified Columns.\nSolicitor\nClassified Advertising\nAll Classified Advertising is charg\ned at 2 cents per word. Cash or\nstamps must accompany all ordera\nl No ad taken for less than 25 cents.\nCHURCH NOTICES\nWEDDING PAGEANT\u2014SaIem If.\nE. Church, Feb. 10, 11, auspices Ep\nworth League. Don\u2019t miss this nova!\nI entertainment.\nI Jan 28-2 t.\nGEORGE WASHINGTON SUF\nPER\u2014Thursday, February 24. Salem\nM. E. Church. Served by the men.\nJan. 28-4tp.\nBAKE Junior Class Pocomoke City\nHigh School. Saturday, January 2f\u201e\nin Eastern Shore Gas Company office,\nbeginning at 1:30 P. M.\njJan. 28-ltp.\nWANTED\nWANTED\u2014A safe, typewriter aad\nadding machine. M. W. Landing.\nJan. 28-It.\nOPENING NEW LOCAL AGENCY\n\u2014Need man immediately to supply\nregular consumers. Start with earn\nings up to $32.50 in a week. Must\nwrite quick. Albert Mills, 4435 Moa\nmouth, Cincinnati, O.\nJan. 28-ltp.\nWANTED \u2014DeaIer for large mana\nfacturer needs a reliable man to assist\nhim with business and collections in\nSomerset County. No peddling. We\nprefer a married man who will appre\nciate steady work with a good in\ncome. For interview write E. C. Lloyd,\n122 N. Division St., Salisbury, Md.\nJan 21,-2t.\nFOR SALE\nGENERAL ELECTRIC REFRIG\nERATOR FOR SALE. Mrs. N. J.\nLewis.\nJan. 28-tf.\nTWO STORAGE ROOMS FOR\nRENT\u2014I. H. Merrill Co.\nDec. 30-tf.\nFOR SALE\u2014Estate Oil Heatrola,\n7000 cubic feet capacity, used leas\nthan one month. Eastern Shore Gas\nCorporation.\nDec. 30-tf.\nFOR SALE\u2014A large assortment of\nii*?ed Oil and Gasoline Stoves at bar\ngain prices. Eastern Shore Gas Co.,\nPocomoke 12-2-tf\nFOR SALE\u2014Lespedeza seed. Write\nfor prices. R. L. Wimbrow, pioneer\ngrower, Snow Hill, Md.\nJan. 21-4tp.\nFOR SALE \u2014One pair good work\nmares, 1200 lbs; pigs, tractor and a\nlot of farm implements. Located at\nmy farm near Cokesbury. Harry T.\nCottman.\nJan. 21-stp.\nFOR SALE\u2014Horses and mules ia\ntruck and car loads. Also Hereford\ncattle all sizes. 100 Black Pole An\ngus. 40 Black calves. Write or wire\nat once. J. F. Teal, Fairfield, lowa.\nJan. 21-3tp.\nHOUSE FOR SALE\u20143 Clarke Are.\nApply Sherman Powell, Marion Sta.,\nMd.\nJan. 21-tf.\nFOR RENT\nFOR RENT\u20146-room house. Wil\ndivide in two apartments. Gus Mason.\nJan 28-tf.\nFOR RENT\u20146-room house, 901\nSecond St. Modem conveniences, f.\nM. Custis.\nDec. 23-tf.\nFOR RENT \u2014House at 911 Clarke\nAvenue, water lights, and bath. Apply\nto William H. Merrill.\nDec. 23-tf.\n5-ROOM APARTMENT FOR RENT\nLights and bath. Henrietta Chatham.\nSept. 24-tf.\nMISCELLANEOUS\nNEED MONEY?\u2014See Worcester\nFinance Co., M. W. Landing, Mgr.\nLocated corner Clarke Ave. and Maple\nStreet., Pocomoke City, Md. Rates\nreasonable.\nJan. 28-tf.\nHAULING OF ALL KlNDS\u2014Spec\nial low prices. Francis E. Young,\nPocomoke, Route 1. Phone 326-W.\nJan 14-4 t.\nDR. G. E. FlNNEY\u2014Graduate Lic\nensed Veterinarian. Onancock, Va.\nPhone 168. Aug.-27-tf\nFeet Hurt? Groh\u2019s Sponge Rubbe*\nArch Supports relieves tired aching\ncalloused feet. For comfort Phons\n128 W or write, Mr. Groh.\nMarch 19-tf.\nNOTICE\u2014Price on hair cutting\u2014\n-25 cents will remain the same at\nShaws.\nJuly 10-tf\nDR. R. I. GIVENS\nDENTIST\nOffice \u2022ver New Callahan\nBuilding\nPhone\u20143l3\nj\nWe have one of the finest equipped\ni dants on the Shore for turning out\nigh class printing.\nFriday, January 28, 1938","height":"25119","width":"20571"}}
